DA  - 1995/06/01
TI  - International Sourcing and Supply Chain Stability
JO  - Journal of International Business Studies
SP  - 343
EP  - 360
VL  - 26
IS  - 2
AB  - An international supply chain is conceptualized as a complex, dynamic system in which disruptions interact with long shipping and lead times to generate costs. Findings from a case study and simulation model indicate that demand-related disruptions created substantial and unexpected costs in terms of expedited shipping, high inventories, and lower demand fulfillment. Production-related disruptions declined over time, but demand-related disruptions did not. Implications for management are discussed.
